##Wuhan Doctors Work Experience: After work, I have to help the Department to rob supplies | story FM

Story

Features, welcome to the story FM. Here, we tell your story with your voice. Every Monday, Wednesday and Friday, all platforms are updated simultaneously.

Click on the picture above to jump to the "story FM" applet and listen to the real person. Remember to add "my little program" , one-click to listen to the whole story Yo!

On the first day of the Lunar New Year, the story FM interviewed five ordinary Wuhan citizens and asked them to tell the real feeling of being in an epidemic area at this time.

Today we are going to broadcast the self-report of a doctor who is now a resident physician in the Department of Cardiology of a third-class hospital in Wuhan.

-1-

Decided to stay behind

My name is Sanzō, and I am now a resident in the department of Cardiology at a third-class hospital in Wuhan.

We've known about the COVID-19 since about the beginning of January. Because many of the doctors at Wuhan's top three hospitals are either Wuhan University or Huazhong University of Science and Technology Graduates, the circle is small, so news travels fast.

At that time, it was a doctor at the Wuhan Central Hospital, who was in the student group, that is, in the class of Concord 15, who sent out this data. As soon as our medical students looked at the CT, they knew it was a viral lung.

At the time, Wuhan central had its patients take genetic tests for the virus at their own expense, and the results were 70% similar to the coronavirus, which is why the doctor was able to call it "the new SARS. ".

Our director is better, in early January he found out the matter and told us in the department.

Then, in the first two weeks of January, our hospital readjusted and prepared for the fever clinic. But when the authorities say, "No one passed on, " it's probably for fear of causing a panic.

■ On the morning of Jan. 23, Hankou Railway Station workers sealed off a metal fence at the entrance to the station. Photo / CAIXIN. com, taken / Ding Gang

I thought I would return home for the Lunar New Year after working twenty-nine Night Shifts and the tenth day of the Lunar New Year, but things got worse.

We got an infection on January 10th, and we started buying our own N95 masks, UV lamps, and medicines.

I didn't think it mattered then. The real panic was on January 23 when the city of Wuhan was sealed off. I had no idea that the virus was so contagious.

My hometown is in a county town below Wuhan. I told my wife to go home, and I couldn't bring myself to go home.

On the 22nd, when I tried to grab the mask, I said I was going back, and the chief said, "you're irresponsible, you've been in a hospital, and you're not afraid of spreading it? "? "

This sentence to the back I think for a few days, New Year 28 I said to the department, I will not go home this year, if there is a task can arrange me on.

Actually, it was one of our colleagues who came in. He went to the fever clinic and told me that he had seen 188 patients in the clinic before the siege, 88 of whom were positive on the CT scan, so the condition was more serious before the siege.

That's why I decided I couldn't go back, because I've been exposed more or less a few times, and just because I don't have a problem doesn't mean I don't have it.

Fortunately, after the city was shut down, through the propaganda of the government, everyone now knew what had happened.

Now, if the CT is positive, we're GONNA call it a probable cause. Because a diagnosis requires a gene box, which we're very short on. But we do have a standard, which is to see if the CT is viral. As long as his CT shows viral lung, this guy should be close to positive for infection.

This virus is very infectious, our department has three or four people in isolation ward, the first two days after genetic testing has been confirmed. Because we have a cardiologist coming in for a respiratory consult, we don't know if we were in contact with the patient, we could have been in that room and got infected.

Then we talked about the main symptoms of infection in the department. It's not about whether you have a fever, or a runny nose, or sneezing. Its first symptom is that we look at the patient for fatigue and appetite. If you have fatigue or loss of appetite, we recommend a CT scan to confirm.

■ A CT image of the viral lung provided by the narrator

-2-

Current situation of Department and hospital

Because we're cardiology, and we're in second-line surgery now. A week before the closure of the city, our hospital began to organize fever clinic, isolation ward. It turns out that one ward has three beds and can accommodate three patients. There's only room for one patient in the isolation ward to prevent cross-contamination. So the original aspiration patients were transferred to our second-line departments.

Our current schedule is a 24-hour shift with a six-day break. As he now opened several more cases of respiratory medicine, he had a good number of doctors transferred to fever clinics and isolation wards. Nurses also smoked a lot, to other departments or to support such a hospital.

SARS, because of large doses of hormone treatment, many patients cured after leaving a serious sequelae. But so far there have been no reports of large doses of hormone use.

If the fever doesn't subside, we'll use a small dose, which is within the normal range. We all use it in the clinic.

But if you get a bad pneumonia, there's always going to be something left behind. Just in case there's pulmonary fibrosis or something. It's probably nothing when you're young, but you're more susceptible to infection when you're old.

At present, all hospitals in Wuhan are basically in the state of no beds, patients can not be admitted, unless you are particularly critical. Like mild and moderate patients, they are sent home to self-isolation, medication, this is no way things.

I now see that the general outpatient clinic is basically no patients, before the hall is full of people, now scattered a few people. But the fever clinic was crowded and there was a long line. And there were more people at night than during the day, probably because they were afraid their neighbors in the neighborhood would know they were coming.

■ On Jan. 22, people with fever crowded a hallway at the Red Cross Hospital. Photo / CAIXIN / Cai Yingli

-3-

Scarce protective equipment

As a second-line doctor, my day job is a little awkward right now. In addition to the time to work, every day is self-isolation, and then in the group to fill out a variety of charity organization donation application form, to help the department rob a material.

Because we do not have a lot of things in the hospital, such as masks, protective clothing, goggles, these things are not.

As a matter of fact, there are strict requirements for the use of materials in isolation wards. For example, a normal surgical mask is only effective for three to four hours, and N95 can last for four to six hours.

But since we're short on supplies, it's GonNa last us 24 hours. Now there is also a phenomenon, such as our second-line department, N95 mask after a day, we take to the tap water, see if it leaks, no leak should still be used, just take alcohol, put it on a UV lamp, and keep using it.

In particular, isolation suits, goggles and N95 are not part of the hospital's normal needs, so they are not particularly large stocks. But we have over 1,000 employees, and with every day we spend, we're running out.

A few days ago, Concord Hospital was the first one to ask for help directly from outside. After they did, our hospitals followed suit and asked for help from society. Yesterday, I saw on Weibo that the nurse of Concord West Hospital didn't have a mask and cut it by herself with the material of operation clothes. They've come this far. They're worse off than us.

Because Wuhan Red Cross Society this material has not been distributed down, anyway I have not received the Red Cross things. So we're basically scrambling for supplies, getting masks from people who care, and then we're doing something for departments and hospitals.

■ On February 1, workers at the Temporary Red Cross warehouse at the Wuhan International Expo Center counted and registered in the warehouse. A number of medical units waiting to receive supplies, until the afternoon only received a small number of leave. Photo / CAIXIN / Ding Gang

-4-

Prepare to be summoned

I'm waiting to be called to the front line. We've been practicing secondary containment for the last two days, including how to dress, and we have a standard procedure. My chief made me memorize it a few times.

Going to the fever clinic my main concern is medical malpractice. I mean, one of the patients was diagnosed, and the family beat up the doctor, and the doctor was severely exposed. And pulling on a doctor's mask and spitting.

Actually the most troublesome is the psychological pressure, but I think my ability to withstand pressure is good.

I am most impressed is the New Year's Day, our department has a girl fever, her mentality collapsed. But she had a common cold and went home to quarantine herself.

I can understand the panic. The virus is important, but it doesn't need to be. Because although it is highly infectious, but its mortality rate is not very high, basically the death of patients more or less combined with some basic diseases, the body is relatively weak, so can not withstand.

My colleague at the fever clinic did his own research and found that the incidence in the 30s was less than 5% . Our Hospital's isolation ward does not appear to have died, a few were discharged after the drug.

The death rate is not high, and we are not so worried.

So it's still a matter of resistance. You might as well take advantage of this time at home, eat well, drink well, rest well, adjust their state of mind, do not believe those folk prescription.

If Shuanghuanglian can inhibit the virus, then I would like to say that boiled water also has the inhibition of it. People wouldn't believe this stuff if they had a little medical sense.
